# 4  IPEmotion Quick Start Guide

#### 4 IPEmotion Quick Start Guide

IPEmotion Quick Setup:  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ESVvkrSapPg

As an introduction to this manual, a high-level overview of the main features is provided.

#### 4.1 Installing IPEmotion and PlugIns

The latest version of the IPEmotion software is available at  www.ipetronik.com . After down-
loading the setup, you can run the installation. The software and plug-ins are only available as a
64 bit setup. The x64 bit application is installed in below directory:

▶ 64-bit C:\Program Files\IPETRONIK\IPEmotion 2024 R2

During the installation process you can choose between different installation options. The main
differences are:

4.1.1 Full Installation

▶ All language packages are installed if not deselected.

▶ The PlugIn Designer development tool is installed.

▶ All standard IPETRONIK PlugIns are installed if not deselected.

4.1.2 Typical Installation

▶ Only the English and local language package related to the computer operating system is

installed when supported by IPEmotion.

▶ The PlugIn Designer development tool is NOT installed.

▶ All standard IPETRONIK PlugIns are installed if not deselected.

4.1.3 User defined installation

▶ Define your own installation settings.

#### 4.2 PlugIns Activation

After installing IPEmotion and the PlugIn, restart IPEmotion and activate the PlugIn in the
Options. You can access the Options from the application menu or directly from the ribbon.
Plug-ins are activated by checking the box. Most PlugIns include technical documentation that
explains the functions supported by the PlugIn. See  "PlugIns " on page 1095 for more details.

4.3.4 Channel configuration and scaling

Now we need to look into the channel scaling options. This is an important configuration to read
your engineering units in IPEmotion. Each channel has the following 3 standard tab sheets.

Figure 4.7 - Channel Configuration

▶ General >for defining channel name & description

▶ Scaling >for scaling sensor input (MIN / MAX) to engineering units

▶ Display >decimal places on the display instruments and axis on charts

The default channel grid consists of columns for:

▶ Active check box

▶ Units (engineering units: V mA, A, bar, PSI, Ohm, etc. )

▶ Physical MIN / MAX (engineering units)

▶ Sensor MIN / MAX (electrical signal to the input)

▶ Sample rate (measurements per second in Hz)

The scaling calculator offers a large range of functions. Basic scaling operations to convert ana-
log measurement in engineering units can be performed in the scaling tab sheet. Select the
sensor mode from the list box and define the sensor range to the expected electrical signal. In
the physical range you can define the engineering unit (bar, rpm, PSI, mm, etc.).

Figure 4.9 - Scaling Calculator

In this example, the ADAM PlugIn supports the analog inputs of the 4017 module VOLT and
CURRENT measurement in different predefined ranges.

IPEmotion offers a sophisticated scaling interface for each PlugIn. The different scaling options
will be explained in  "Scaling calculator" on page 207

Sensor mode is PlugIn-specific. Not all modules and inputs support all types

of sensor modes like voltage, current, strain or temperature measurement.

The supported functions depend on the hardware. Some hardware systems

only support one mode with one static measurement range e.g. +-10 Volt.

#### 4.4 ACQUISITION setting up data storage

Data storage is very important and therefore IPEmotion is very easy to use in this aspect. You
just need to add the available channel (left side) to the right window to include them in the stor-
age group.

Figure 4.10 - Acquisition Setting

▶ Format: When you hit the store button data storage is enabled and IPEmotion stores data in

the selected file format.

▶ Prefix: The prefix is a static name which is put in front of the data file name. After the prefix,

an index increments from 0 to n to differentiate the storage files. The number increments by
one for each file generated.

▶ Marker & marker name operated with a hotkey: For adding text information to the data file,

you can define a marker channel. The marker can then be operated using a keyboard com-
bination (hotkey) defined in the OPTIONS. When you hit the defined hotkey, a pop up win-
dow appears and the comment can be added during recording process.

4.4.1 Defining storage trigger conditions

Event-Based Data Storage in IPEmotion RT & PC:  https://youtu.be/IsXKJafjAW4

Three different storage modes are supported:

▶ One file per acquisition: In the default storage mode, data is recorded when the store button

is activated.

▶ Cyclical storage: In this mode, a new data file is automatically generated after a period of

time has elapsed. The cycle can be defined in second [s], minutes [m] or hours [h].

▶ Triggered data storage: However, in many cases data storage should be started based on

trigger events. Triggered data storage with static pre-trigger, post trigger time and the start
& stop trigger conditions can be defined through the formula parser which will be explained
in  "ACQUISITION" on page 1297  .

#### 4.5 VIEW Displaying live data in instruments

There is a large list of instruments available to build your graphical user interface to show live
data in different analog and digital instruments. You can also add action buttons and operate
switches to trigger functions or to set output channels. You can modify the mimics during display
and data storage which is a very comfortable function. There is no need to stop the acquisition
process if you like to modify the screen design. The configuration options of each instrument will
be explained in detail, later on.

#### 4.7 ANALYSIS analyze recorded data

Deep Dive - Post Processing:  https://youtu.be/TtVp4hAKjLU

IPEmotion - Althen Graphtec Data Analysis:  http://youtu.be/kDKKfy23d5o

If you like to perform data analysis functions you need to navigate the ribbon to the tab sheet
ANALYSIS. In the analysis work area you can display recorded data in different instruments like
Yt, YX, Maps and Video displays. The main features are applying zoom, stretching and moving
functions to the charts. With cursor lines you can add a table with measurement statistics. The
mimics you define in the analysis section are converted to a report.

#### 4.8 REPORTING generate a report

In the REPORTING work space you can launch a layout designer to customize your standard
report layout in regard to the header and footer sections. You can add text, tables, pictures and
graphical elements directly to report without starting the layout designer. These changes are not
saved to the standard template. When you restart the application the manual entries are
removed. However, if you add graphical elements using the layout designer and if you save
these changes to your default template they will be available any time you open up the report
again.
